article.headline: Two Seattle stars score 20 each
article.linkText: Jackson, Bird thrive as Storm crush Stars
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Sue Bird turned up the intensity in her play and
had her most productive day in a while.

The Seattle Storm guard scored 20 points, and the Storm used a
dominating first half to coast to a 76-52 victory over the San
Antonio Silver Stars.

"Honestly, I came into this game wanting to be aggressive,"
Bird said. "I think the last couple of games I haven't been as
aggressive as I should be."

Bird hadn't scored more than nine points in any of her previous
five games but she helped the Storm snap a two-game losing streak.
Seattle led 43-20 at halftime as the Storm's starters outscored San
Antonio's 37-8 in the first half.

Lauren Jackson added 20 points, and Sheri Sam had 11 points and
10 rebounds for Seattle. The Storm (9-4) lead the Western
Conference by a half-game over Los Angeles.

"There is no doubt in my mind we're capable of these type of
games night in and night out," Storm coach Anne Donovan said.

Bird said her recent struggles weren't a slump, but she had made
only 12-of-40 shots the last five games. Bird made 8-of-11 on
Thursday, including 4 of 5 from 3-point range.

"If you're shooting well, you can't get too caught up in it,
and if you're in a slump you can't get too caught up in it," Bird
said. "One night you can be on fire and the next night you can't
hit anything. It happens."

Adrienne Goodson led San Antonio with 10 points, but the Silver
Stars shot only 29 percent in the first half and 35 percent for the
game. Leading scorer Marie Ferdinand managed just six points.

Seattle played without second-leading scorer Betty Lennox, who
had surgery after breaking her nose last week against Houston.

The Storm, the highest-scoring team in the WNBA, jumped to a
14-2 lead and was never threatened. Seattle broke the 70-point
barrier for only the third time in eight games.

"When you're playing a team like Seattle, who definitely has
the best starting five in the league, and you don't play your
hardest you are going to get beat like that," San Antonio coach
Dee Brown said. "Right now, I think we're just going through the
motions ... hopefully it will turn around."

San Antonio led only once, at 2-0. The Silver Stars trimmed the
lead to single digits once during the first half at 17-8, but
Seattle scored 18 of the next 25 points to build the lead to 20.
